Welcome to our Game State project!

Authors: Aidan M., Liam F., Matthew M.

Project Goals: 
  Game state represents the accumulated events and conditions at any moment in a football match, including score, substitutions remaining, red 
cards, and time. Each of these events is irreversible and directly shapes how teams behave strategically. Goals shift match incentives 
immediately, forcing losing teams to attack more aggressively while encouraging leading teams to protect their advantage. Substitutions are 
limited resources that alter tactics, formations, and player roles, and are used differently depending on whether a team is chasing the game or 
preserving a lead. Time remaining in the match tightens these strategic pressures, reducing the window for creating or preventing goals. Red 
cards impose significant structural disadvantages but may still be strategically optimal in situations like DOGSO, where conceding a red card 
prevents a high-probability scoring opportunity.

  This project analyzes these components collectively, alongside match difficulty (team strength differences and home/away status), to develop 
a prescriptive win-probability model. By constructing a multidimensional Pareto frontier, the model identifies when key decisions such as 
committing a tactical foul, making substitutions to defend a lead, or making substitutions to chase a deficit produce positive expected value. 
Unlike traditional descriptive tools, this model is designed to advise coaches by mapping game state inputs to optimal decision timings.


Installation:
  Download the desired data, the suggestion is '5-minute-breakdown-All-Final.csv' and 'All_Data_Final_Fixed.csv' as they are the primary data 
used for training the models. Once the programs are downloaded they can simplely be run.

Information:
  When using the API call a premium membership on football-data.org is required to collect the needed information. Furthermore the league 
codes need to be changed as well as year depending on which league and year is being collected. For data collection the program was 
originally built around La Liga as it was the first to be collected but it can be easily adjusted for any league available on football-
data.org.
